We can calculate the ratios step‐by‐step using the End values from the provided statements.

(1) Current Ratio  
= Total Current Assets / Total Current Liabilities  
= 29,413,723.95 / 8,028,630.43  
≈ 3.66

(2) Gross Profit Margin  
= (Gross Profit / Total Revenue) × 100%  
= (8,372,608.70 / 28,572,608.70) × 100%  
≈ 29.33%

(3) Debt to Asset Ratio  
Here the only liabilities provided are current liabilities so we use:  
= Total Liabilities / Total Assets  
= 8,028,630.43 / 39,772,748.32  
≈ 0.20

(4) Net Profit Margin  
= (Net Profit / Total Revenue) × 100%  
= (3,744,117.89 / 28,572,608.70) × 100%  
≈ 13.11%

(5) Cash to Current Debt Ratio  
We use the Ending Balance in Cash and Cash Equivalents (from cash flow statement) divided by Total Current Liabilities.  
= 7,077,270.00 / 8,028,630.43  
≈ 0.88

(6) Free Cash Flow (FCF)  
Normally defined as Cash Flow from Operating Activities minus Capital Expenditures. Here:  
FCF = (-10,442,735.47) – (2,479,994.53)  
= -12,922,730.00

(7) Return on Assets (ROA)  
= (Net Profit / Total Assets) × 100%  
= (3,744,117.89 / 39,772,748.32) × 100%  
≈ 9.42%

Thus, the final answer is:

  }
